              I'm not really sure about this... <img src="http://episteme.arstechnica.com/groupee_common/emoticons/icon_wink.gif" alt="Wink" width="15" height="15"><!--graemlin:;)--><BR><BR>I recall Wikipedia's article on it to be quite good, but I can see if I can find something better at a later time (at work now).<BR><BR>As for Schrodenger's cat, I recall it was originally supposed to illustrate the absurdity of quantum mechanics.  There is no way a cat can be both alive and dead.  <BR><BR>Over the decades it has evolved to illustrate that an object (the cat in this case) DOES (not can, but does) exist in a superposition of states until it is measured, then one single value will be seen (e.g. alive/dead).  Of course, this goofiness is keep in the realm of the very small due to Planck's constant being tiny.<BR><BR>EDIT:  <A HREF="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_principle#Derivation" TARGET=_blank>This derivation</A> illustrates that there is nothing inherently special about Heisenberg's uncertainty principle, as ANY two (Hermitian) operators can be shown to follow that relationship due to the Cauchy-Schwartz inequality.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
