              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by river-wind:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by Fate Amenable to Change:<BR>To measure the frequency accurately you will need to measure it over a certain time, which is likely to mean a certain displacement... <BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>Well, that's simple enough.  Do others agree that this is a worthwhile summation? </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Not really. This goes back to which interpretation of QM you subscribe to. Fate's description is known as the hidden variable interpretation. Even though we can't measure the position and moment at the same time, the particle still has a well defined position and momentum.<BR><BR>Most physicists will agree that this is incorrect. It's not we can't measure with accuracy. It's that the particle itself does not have a well defined momentum or position. The particle itself doesn't know. <BR><BR>A free space electron, such as the one coming out of my electron gun, is known as a wave packet. It is actually comprised of a summation of waves of many possible momenta. It's not that we can't measure with 100% accuracy both the position and momentum. Rather, although the electron is still zero size, it is delocalized, and exists in a region of space with certain probability. (this should not be confused with string theory, where particles are of nonzero size.)

              

              
              
