            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">Originally posted by sckmcck:<BR>Not really. This goes back to which interpretation of QM you subscribe to. Fate's description is known as the hidden variable interpretation. Even though we can't measure the position and moment at the same time, the particle still has a well defined position and momentum.<BR><BR>Most physicists will agree that this is incorrect.<BR> </div></BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR>Yes.  To elaborate on this a little, a particle can be in a well-defined, or pure state, yet still not have a well defined position and/or momentum.<BR><BR>As an optics guy, I always resort to photons to explain things.  Photons have a polarization, which is just the direction the electric field oscillates.  I can have a vertically polarized photon, which is an exactly known state.  If I put it through a vertical polarizer (A device which only lets through vertical polarization), it will go through 100% of the time -- I know the state exactly.  If I put it through a horizontal polarizer, it will be blocked 100% of the time.  I can also have a horizontally polarized photon, which is likewise well defined, and is transmitted/blocked by the horizontal/vertical polarizer.<BR><BR>The trick is, I can also have a diagonally polarized photon.  This is yet another pure, completely known state, it is just rotated 45 degrees.  I can use a diagonal polarizer, and it goes through, again, 100% of the time.  The trick is, now if I measure this photon with a horizontal or vertical polarizer, I will get either answer (blocked or transmitted) with 50% probability.<BR><BR>It isn't that I lacked knowledge of how horizontal or vertical my photon was -- it simply was in a state that wasn't well defined as horizontal or vertical.  This happens because 'horizontalness' and 'diagonalness' are what we refer to in a technical sense as 'non-commuting observables.'  In more plain language, that means that they can't both be well defined for a photon.<BR><BR>A small minority of physicists try to hold on to the notion that my diagonally polarized photon 'internally knew' whether it was going to be vertical or horizontal -- a local hidden variable theory.  However, these theories have been almost (but perhaps not quote) conclusively disproven by Bell inequality tests.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
