              <BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">There's only two factors related to The Uncertainty Principle (although these two factors affect a bajillion others). </div></BLOCKQUOTE>Just to make sure we're perfectly clear here, the uncertainty principle holds for <I>any</I> two observables (like position and momentum) whose operators don't commute.  In other words, if the two don't have a common basis of eigenstates, then you'll have an uncertainty relationship.<BR><BR>In the real world, measuring one variable collapses the wavefunction into a well-defined state (say momentum).  This has the consequence of making any other observable with which momentum does not commute be ill-defined (like position).  It drops out quite nicely when you do a Fourier transform from p-&gt;x.<BR><BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content">What this also means is that the more accurately you measure the two known items, the less accurate any information about the third will be. </div></BLOCKQUOTE>No.  Uncertainty is a relation between any <I>two</I> observables whose operators (like P and X) don't commute.<BR><BR>I'll try to dig up a more elementary explanation of the uncertainty between p and x using wave packets so you can get an idea of how the math works without having to deal with Fourier transforms/etc.<BR><BLOCKQUOTE class="ip-ubbcode-quote"><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-title">quote:</div><div class="ip-ubbcode-quote-content"><BR>The trick is, I can also have a diagonally polarized photon. This is yet another pure, completely known state, it is just rotated 45 degrees. I can use a diagonal polarizer, and it goes through, again, 100% of the time. The trick is, now if I measure this photon with a horizontal or vertical polarizer, I will get either answer (blocked or transmitted) with 50% probability. </div></BLOCKQUOTE>This exaplanation, I like it.

              

              
              
